04539nam a22007575i 9781501724626DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017246267 a10.7591/97815017246262doi  a(DE-B1597)515298  a(OCoLC)1129143226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN2636.P3bR28 1999 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a792/.09443/612211 aRavel, Jeffrey S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Contested Parterre :bPublic Theater and French Political Culture, 1680-1791 /cJeffrey S. Ravel. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 chart, 1 map, 1 table, 11 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Political Culture, Print, and Performance -- t1. Parterre Practices in Eighteenth-Century Paris -- t2. Origins of the Contested Parterre, 1630-80 -- t3. "The Parterre Becomes an A~tor," 1680-1725 -- t4. Policing the Parisian Parterre, 169/-1/51 -- t5. Policing the Parterre in Paris and the Provinces, 1751-89 -- t6. The Parterre and French National Identity in the Eighteenth Century -- tAfterword -- tAppendix: List of Spectators in Paris Parterres by Social Category and Theater, 1717-68 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the playhouses of eighteenth-century France, clerks and students, soldiers and merchants, and the occasional aristocrat stood in the pit, while the majority of the elite sat in loges. These denizens of the parterre, who accounted for up to two-thirds of the audience, were given to disruptive behavior that culminated in full-scale riots in the last years before the Revolution. Offering a commoner's eye view of the drama offstage, this fascinating history of French theater audiences clearly demonstrates how problems in the parterre reflected tensions at the heart of the Old Regime.Jeffrey S. Ravel vividly depicts the scene in the parterre where the male spectators occupied themselves shoving one another, drinking, urinating, and confronting the actors with critiques of the performance. He traces the futile efforts of the Bourbon Court-and later its Enlightened opponents-to control parterre behavior by both persuasion and force. Ravel describes how the parterre came to represent a larger, more politicized notion of the public, one that exposed the inability of the government to accommodate the demands of French citizens. An important contribution to debates on the public sphere, Ravel's book is the first to explore the role of the parterre in the political culture of eighteenth-century France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aTheater audienceszFrancezParis. 0aTheaterzFrancezParisxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheaterzFrancezParisxHistoryy18th century. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501724626423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501724626.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG